Adriene, thank you for being my guide toward liberation from PMS symptoms. I just completed my fifth yoga journey with you (doing them in order). During the 30 Days of Yoga, when I hit PMS week, I had to pause the journey and opt instead for practices like Yoga for Cramps and PMS, Yoga for Women, and Yoga for Headaches. Now, following the onset of PMS, I continue with my regular program, and by the end of practice, I'm like, "What symptoms?" I used to feel completely helpless and dominated by my hormones. Now, I feel that my foundation of health is stronger than any effect they can have on me. This service, which you were born for, is life-changing to the global community, and you have my (our) everlasting gratitude. üíñ

I am writing this with a deep disappointment that drowns my heart at the moment.

I was looking forward to this last step of the journey for so long. It took way more than 30 days to complete this 30 day journey, so it would mean so much more to have a fulfilling end to this. Yet, with the decision to go ‚Äòmute‚Äô for the last day‚Äôs session, I was left with no guidance just because I can‚Äôt see. I rely on audio guidance to follow your routines because I can‚Äôt see without my glasses on. And today I sat on the mat with excitement and joy, just to realize I am robbed from the satisfaction of completing this journey. 

If you forget about me for a second, how are others with small screens supposed to follow those moves? Or people who have seeing disabilities? If there was a series with no verbal guidance, some people might choose to follow that one, maybe they prefer that. But I chose to follow this one from the beginning just to see it change fundamentally right at the end. 

I am very sad that it ended like this. I have absolute zero motivation to start a new journey. I feel betrayed and I feel the disappointment choking me down my throat. Oh my Gosh! This is my 2nd time around with Dedicate, having gone through all the 30-Day challenges during COVID, and then circling back to repeat the cycle again. (Can't wait to start the 2021 Breathe sequence!!!) I think I may have finally cracked the code on my struggle with the Day 30 yoga -- and the mixed blessing of not being guided by Adriene's voice. This time, I actually WATCHED the video first, and recorded MY voice, guiding myself from posture to posture. And now I am going to DO it, listening to my recording and having the video to keep me company. BUT the amazing thing already was just the experiencing of watching Adriene moving through the whole sequence/vinyasa. It was like watching a dance. Adriene, you move with such grace and intention. I felt it in a whole new way -- maybe because all the other days i don't WATCH you all that carefully, I mostly listen, and often close my eyes. But now I feel like I can sense and SEE the poses differently. Can't wait to try out my Day 30. Sorry to ramble, but I am so moved...

I lost my partner earlier this year in May from cancer at the age of 33. The all-consuming nature of the grief has left me feeling very alien at times, and the pain of the heartbreak is often disassociative. How extraordinarily fortunate have I been then, amidst all of the sadness and despair, that a friend of mine led me to your channel and this Dedicate series in particular. So many of your lessons and the teaching that accompanies the movement have resonated with me in a way I never would have envisaged before my partner passed. The idea of coming back to your centre and always having your breath, the idea of owning and loving whatever moment you arrive in, that it is ok and that your journey is one of evolution and kindness to yourself and others. The idea that you have to show up for yourself to show up for others! I laid there at the end of today's practice quietly weeping, remembering where I was months ago, picturing my partner watching comfortably and pain free from afar with a smile on her face because she could see me smiling and strong. How beautiful that we all share on this journey together, through the pain and the doubt and the sadness it is so life-affirming to connect to the bigger picture and sit in the knowledge that there are people taking the journey with you, carrying an open heart and mind. Thank you Adriene, for being a wonderful teacher and a beautiful human being, for the positive ripples you set in motion every day. Namaste üôè

Well done everyone :) About two months ago I did my first yoga practice ever, the next day I started HOME, then went on to do Dedicate. It changed my life - well, Adriene changed my life. I got so much stronger (both physically and mentally) and learning to breathe right was such a revelation.

I started doing yoga with adriene 100 days or so ago because quarantine was stressing me out, my chronic back pain, and I'm maybe the least flexible person in the world.  Her 30 days are nice easy chunks for me to stay motivated to do yoga every day and short enough they don't feel like too much of a commitment.
I have to admit, last week I had a bit of a breakdown.  When I started, I couldn't touch my toes (really even my ankles), reach my hands over my head,  or bend more than few inches forward when seated.  And last week it hit me, even though I've been at it for months I don't feel any closer to touching my toes, can't reach my hands over my head, can't bend, can't balance. Regularly I find myself completely unable to replicate a pose she gives no adjustments for (happy baby? more like me crying).  I felt like I'm doing everything wrong and so I decided I had to try harder.  On a straight-legged seat fold I pushed as hard as I could and heard a horrible pop. My neck and back went out again. I could hardly move the next day.  Since I'd started yoga my pain had been much better, but suddenly even that was gone.
I realized that I'm doing the best I can, progress will come if it does, and I am slowly at least getting stronger.  Maybe I'll never touch my toes or have my heels down in downward dog. There are worst things in life.

This is the second 30-day yoga journey I have completed during the COVID-19 quarantine. It is the one thing that has been consistent for me through this time -- Adriene's gentle, joyful, soothing guidance; my commitment to showing up; trying to learn patience and acceptance and some grace. Thank you forever for this. The 30th-day is such a magical thing. I wish I could explain it. It took my by surprise 31 days ago and I felt like I was being restored. And today, on my second 30th Day -- while not a surprise -- was wonderful also. The past week my heart has been broken, and I have been filled with outrage and sadness and disgust and horror and by the explosive videos of racial violence and unfettered police brutality and chaos (that certainly has been going on for ages, but without cell phone coverage). Thank you, Adriene for the gift of luxury of offering my some moments of peace and reprieve.

Adriene, I am over a year later than almost everyone here and I don't know if you'll read this, but I really wanted to say a couple of things.

You have been so inspirational throughout this entire journey, and have helped me love my body and take care of it, even OUT of practice time. Everyday I notice that I sit a little straighter at my desk, I'm more mindful of my movements, I observe my breaths...
I've been reading all these comments about people feeling more loved and connecting to themselves and randomly crying during yoga, but for the most time I felt like it wasn't working, and I was doing something wrong.
But in the last few days I realized I was wrong. I have improved so much, and I am so proud of myself for going on this journey, even if it was difficult, even if I missed two days. Honestly, the first time I've ever cried and felt like I really loved myself was Day Eight, Meditate. But then that feeling started to fade again, until now. You have helped me stay so connected to myself and my body, and I am so grateful.
I loved today's practice as well, I really enjoyed the fact that the mic was off, and I think I connected to myself better (even though I did peek at you!) and I really enjoyed everything overall.

One last thing:
Usually I don't say 'Namaste' or do that because I didn't really resonate with it and I felt pretty alone anyway. But you know what? I cried when this was over. And today, for the first time, I said 'Namaste' to you and to everyone who has done this, and I meant it. I really did.

My partner Paula and I Just finished the course yesterday. And thank you for everything. We are in Mumbai in a complete lock down. Life right now is full on anxiety and stress. Lot of work is happening despite the lock down and  at the same time you have to deal with the hot indian summer. The difference between a day and a night was  getting blurred for a few days.  You and this course is what kept us going so strong. You made us fall in love with what we have. Paula is from Vancouver and I am from Pune so we both have been heavily exposed to Yoga in our own way. She was exposed to it in a very Vancouver Hipster way and I have been exposed to it as I went to a school where it was part of our Physical Training exams. Many Indian schools make it compulsory.  But when you don't get introduced to yoga in a right way you never like it. We didn't like it much either. But these 30 days we practised it with you for ourselves. Not because its a trend or not because it's compulsory in the school. And oh boy wasn't it a completely different experience. Thank you for guiding us so seamlessly and making it feel effortless.  Will continue to take your guidance. And will continue practicing. Lots of love and Light.

After I started to see a therapist for the first time, I began slowly identifying some significant experiences that shaped my life, my mind, my body. She noticed I was holding my breath a lot, so I did a couple of days of short breathing practice and found your YouTube channel after investing in a yoga mat and some sweet pants. I hoped I could go a little deeper with some mind-body connections. I had some early damage to my psycho-spiritual sacrum.

The yoga practice I built for myself just wouldn't have happened without you. It was so immediately, immensely helpful to have a guide who would speak to my own specific concerns - uniting right and left, sun and moon, masculine and feminine, mind and body. Finding the source of 20 years of mind-body disassociation was intense for me, and related to an experience I had on the early internet with a pedophilic predator. How fitting that an altogether different teacher on the internet would help me process the way this had affected me for so long.

I made it through your Dedicate 30-day yoga journey after some basic instruction videos. Along the way, I went to a couple of group classes locally, feeling way more confident than I would have if I had gone in cold. I'm now about 5 days out from the end, and find a new video each day in your channel for that day's yoga practice. I wake up, every day, looking forward to the time I get to spend working toward a united mind and body, heart and soul. I used to feel so separate from my body. Thank you for helping me live more joyfully, and with a wholeness I've not had for a very, very long time.

Finally finished, only took me to December 27th! This 30 days of community practice ushered in a very powerful 2019 for me. I was in a car horrific car accident two years ago and have PTSD because of the incident and am now partially disabled. My body hurt all the time, I was constantly nauseous, had migraines, it made me lay in bed all day. I felt like I had no control over my body, I was depressed, I was in so much pain, physically and emotionally. Dedicating this time to my health and healing has made such a drastic change in both my physical and emotional trauma. I no longer lay in bed all the time, I wake up early and excited to eat breakfast and do yoga. I truly believed that my pain would be unmanageable, but yoga has given me such a wonderful gift. The physical healing has been a catalyst for healing my emotional trauma. Today as we began in meditation I just began to cry, I am so much stronger than I was 30 days ago, I am so much stronger than I was 2 years ago. Thank you Adriene, you are truly a blessing. Before this I had closed myself off in fear of getting hurt, you have shown me to be kind and gentle to myself. I will spread your positive mission from here on out and take yoga on my journey. -Jacquelin, 22, Oregon

It‚Äôs dark in the tunnel and yet I can see
a light at the end far away from me. 


The light changes shape from year to year 
always adapting to my innermost fear. 


The fear of being away from home
the light looking quite like my brother Jerome


The fear of being stuck in the city 
a countryside house made of light ‚Äì look how pretty!


The fear of not ever being enough
an image of me looking skinny and tough

Everytime one fear is out of the way 
another one creeps in and threatens to stay

Then one day I learned to breathe properly 
and suddenly I could clearly see
the light at the end of the tunnel was me.

My goal was to do 60 days of exercise, but I was cautious on what I chose to do since I was ana- and ortho- rexic for many years. I'm completely recovered, but doing something everyday sometimes taps into my unhealthy mindset. I decided to see if there was a 30 day yoga series and found Dedicate. :) 

When today's practice started, I wondered how it would go without coaching. But then I realized it was really cool to be able to think "I can guide a practice on my own!" Half-way through Dedicate, I was able to do puppy pose, and forearm plank without clasping my hands - without doing which usually irritates my forearms weirdly. And today!! I didn't flop down going "slowly" from plank to cobra-set-up!!! I've never ever not had to flop the last few inches! :D I was so excited!

At one point, a voice in my head said, "Re-do that. You weren't holding the muscles you were supposed to. You tensed there and could hurt this.." which all sounds good, but as I started trying to redo it correctly,  I got in this not so good loop. Then I remembered all the times you said, "And if you're doing this, that's okay, too." and I stopped myself, so thank you for that gentle guidance and reminders you incorporate into every video. :)

I also loved loved the background music! So pretty and inspiring! Thank you for this journey, Adriene! I plan on doing last year's 30 days next. See you and Benji there. :)

I'm finishing this almost 3 months in, but I did it. I started this, day 30, off thinking about how difficult the journey has been. Throughout this time I suffered from an allergy attack and asthma attack simultaneously, which left me recuperating for 2 weeks, and bouts of digestive problems that left me with a diagnosis of IBS and waiting to get tested for endometriosis. In the in-betweens, I've been coming back to this challenge, determined to finish and give my body the extra love it needs right now. By the end of this video, I was left thinking of all of the good things so far this year: getting hired permanently at my job after being a temp for over a year and a half, getting my health exemption in the mail and being able to do my taxes without owing money, starting to look for a house to call my own, and nurturing relationships with those I love and watching those relationships grow and flourish. My practice ended with my cat, Weasley, putting his paw on my face during savasana, making me laugh. I couldn't have ended this journey on a better, more positive note. Thank you so much, Adriene <3 I look forward to next year's 30 day journey with you again

I then sat up straight in prayer pose, I sent love to drivers who piss me off when I'm on the road, I sent love to so many who frustrate me like my ex, I sent love and gratitude to everything and everyone, just sending warm light love outwards.

So, I'm 6 weeks late but I did it! I have to admit, when we started this journey I HATED downward dog because it always hurt my wrists. But, as you pointed out early on that we would need to build the muscles up. Well, I believe that has happened. Along with learning that "clawing through the fingers" really helps. I've come to really like this pose, now. I loved the music and even though I was a little worried about following along, I felt that most of the time I seemed to understand what was going to happen next. It also gave me a sense of relief when I saw you have to reset on the pose where we hold the foot back and stretch the other arm out. As we were doing it on the first leg, I was still struggling with balance. I've always felt that I had good balance but as I struggled with this pose suddenly felt "older" at not being able to be steady. Then, out of the corner of my eye, I thought I saw you reset so backed it up and sure enough, you did. It made me realize that even the yoga teacher can lose her balance, maybe it wasn't just me. Thank you for this journey!

I started this 30 day yoga journey at the beginning of a new quarter in school, and it has helped me in so many ways. Medical school has been so challenging with so much information coming at you so fast and there's a lot pressure to perform well on multiple exams every week. There's virtually no time to wind down, but this 30 day series has forced me to set aside time every day for myself to de-stress and come back to my body. This last day was quite an emotional release. Like opening a pressure valve, I was able to feel everything I've been putting aside for the sake of survival. Thank you, Adrienne, for your amazing guidance and quirky sense of humor! I will keep coming back to your videos; I love your genuine personality. Keep shining your light!

Quotes that resonated throughout the journey:
Day 1 Discern: "Notice your transitions, they are the most important."
Day 3 Observe: "You are both the observed and the observer."
Day 8 Meditate: "All you can control is your movements, which control how you feel."
Day 9 Divine: "The divine presence in me recognizes the divine presence in you."
Day 11 Courage: "May we always have the courage to see the truth."
Day 12 Curate: "You are ultimately responsible for your own happiness."
Day 14 Grace: "Grace is different for each of us, different day to day." 
Day 16 Dulce: "How you treat yourself is going to influence or dictate how you treat others."
Day 23 Joyful: "Part of finding the joy for me is giving myself permission to participate and engage in activities and practices that support me being me. Authentically me, so I'm not wearing a disguise or hiding- but I'm putting myself in situations where I can safely explore who I am. So that I can get strong and be steady within that. Even on a really windy day like today."


Every moment has been a gift. 
Namaste, everyone,
Namaste, Adriene

I started this series on 2/1/2019 and just finished a few minutes ago on 3/2/2019.  I wanted to be healthier and even lose weight this year, but I needed a form of exercise that wouldn't be to hard on my joints and something I actually wouldn't mind waking up and doing everyday.  For January, I just switched between hip-hop tabata and novice yoga (mostly just corework and spinal balance), then I came across this 30-day challenge.  It was the only one I could actually afford--a LOT of 30-day yoga subscriptions are advertised on social media, and plus I wanted to see if yoga was right for me.


As it turns out, it very much was.  During this journey, there were a few things in particular I learned about myself and my practice.


1) It turns out I was more familiar with a lot of the poses than I thought, especially cobbler's pose (butterfly), planks, etc.  


2) I absolutely need to get a new yoga mat.  The one I had was a little too slippery, but I bought it three years ago and barely used it, so I had no idea until now.  I think I'll get a cork one.


3) I'm a teacher, which requires me to talk a *lot*, but it wasn't until I started this journey that I realized how little and shallow I was actually breathing in my daily life.  I became much more conscious of that.  Remembering to breathe actually got me through a few stressful times this month, especially during my voice acting audition.


4) While I didn't lose as much weight, there were other major changes my body went through.  I found that I was sleeping better without supplements, and my metabolism and digestioni had *much* improved.


However--and admittedly--there were a couple days during the month I wasn't sure I'd complete all 30 days.  Those were the times when I had to skip on a session and simply double up the next day, or simply do a short practice on my own due to schedule constraints.  Even yesterday--which would be day 29--completing day 30 felt like a long shot.  Maybe because I wasn't sure I'd feel like doing it today.  Maybe because I was the only one within my immediate circle going on this journey.  But I didn't feel I had to keep going--I simply *wanted* to.  As someone who hadn't done yoga since 3rd Grade gym class, that was a huge step for me.


So I finished Day 30.  I didn't land all the poses (such as tree, stepping through from downward dog or ninja), but I got most of the flow down.  Even though there were no oral instructions, this video felt like a practical final exam, an amalgamation of all I had learned, with the music being my guide.  I was pleasantly surprised how easy each movement came to me. 


By the cooldown, especially when the complete Dedicate theme song, started playing, I was tearing up.  It was the perfect reprise, and a reminder that I, on my own, got up at 4 or 5 in the morning and did this practice for a whole month. Not because anyone told me to, but I chose to take care of myself.  This is something I had neglected for such a long time, especially since living in Tokyo for the past six years.  By the time the video ended, I was in complete tears, finally succumbing to my simultaneous pride and humility.  When I finally stopped crying, I simply told myself, "I did it.  I actually did it."


I'm going to continue on to your Weight Loss series and other videos, but I want say thank you *so* much for your guidance and I wish you the best of luck in your journey as well.  Namaste.

I've never done a non-verbal practice before and while I was looking at the screen more often times than not, I was happy to have only my thoughts directing my motions and my body doing more of what it needed rather than what an instructor was telling/challenging it to do. The motions I took were my demands, not someone else's which I can be sometimes disturbingly used to and even dependent on. The wordless practice made my mind so peaceful in ways it hadn't been before in a yoga practice. This truly was liberating and empowering! I hope to be just as great as a yoga guide in the future as this should be the ultimate mission of yoga. Namaste c:

I've finished this beautiful journey 4 days ago. What can I say...Going on this journey truly was the best choice I could make. I started out a little later but it still was the very beginning of a new year and I'm truly greatful for the opportunity. I've faced different things throughout the practices. In the beginning I had almost no balance and was yawning like never before. Not because I was bored or tired or something but because I actually could breathe deeply and well for the first time in many years. My heart was racing through the first 10 or so practices and I couldn't control my breath but things got much better later. I can't even say when but at some point I started noticing that my clumsy flow started being...what???...somewhat graceful. And. I. L O V E D. It.
I've gained balance and strength. I've found my posture (actually started feeling when my spine feels wrong. Now it always wants to be in the lovely "head over heart, heart over pelvis" position.)

The most important - I just feel better now. Awake and stable. Stability is the main thing I've been always trying to find. And now I feel it more and more and accept the possibility of going off track sometimes but I guess...I'll always be able to find myself again somewhere in the Quiet Mountain.

Adrienne, 
So I've been watching you for awhile now and I feel that after completing two of your 30 day yoga programs, I feel it's time to address my experience. I love so many things about your sessions. I love how you talk us through each move and show us how to breathe. I love how you apply everything on the mat to everything off the mat. I really loved dedicating my mornings to yoga with you. I thank you for your commitment as well. 

Now, I have to take a moment to request two things. If I had my way, you would make each session a little bit longer. I really love what you do and what you are helping me do for myself. I would love it if you could shoot for a minimum of 30 minutes. What I normally do: Each morning, I start on my own and warm myself up, then I hit play and do your video with you. However, I always have another one of your previous videos ready in another tab so that I can switch to it after the first one finishes. That way I could have more time for myself and if I still needed or wanted more, I would continue as your video ends. I LOVE IT!

The second request is that you would make a 365 Day Series. I would just love to flow with you and find what feels good for an entire year. I feel like dedicating myself with one teacher could really allow me to dive deeper and deeper into consciousness and create a lasso with  your energy. I love how far I've come and now that the 30 days are over....I find myself wanting more! It was so easy to just click on the next day and know that there would be continuity and consistency in what we had done in the previous sessions. 

I really want to thank you for dedicating your time and energy to us all around the globe. The divinity in me recognizes the divinity in you. Namaste.

P.S. I cried with you, too!

Thank you, Adriene, for another great series and for being the best teacher I could've found. Last year I finally got into yoga thanks to your videos, and I've been practicing with you almost daily since TRUE. It has made me feel so much stronger and more confident, and more than that. Your calm and positive attitude is so amazing that you've become my inner yoga voice, I carry you around in my head everywhere off the mat. I'm not into mantras, but I love your quotes. Several times a day I randomly remember to find the length in the front and ground in the back, take the deepest, loving breath I've taken all day, to relax my shoulders and lift the corners of my mouth... and it always makes me smile. You taught me how to be mindful and kinder to myself as well as others - without even trying!

I've missed a few days of this series due to not having time or energy and ended up finishing a full week later, but I don't mind at all, because even a day later, every single practice was still exactly what I needed that day! I swear you're a magician. Or maybe I'm just exactly where I need to be.

And it's so very fitting that I did this last practice today, as I'm at a strange place in my life right now. I've just finished watching the last series of my favorite show. I'm losing my job and have no idea where I'll work next. Even my relationship is kind of falling apart... It all added up and I've started this year feeling like my whole life is going to end in a few months. But then I realized I'm looking at it all wrong. Every end is also a beginning. Life goes on. I'm going to find a new job, family issues will work out one way or another, broken things can be replaced by new, better ones and I'll find a new show to watch. Tomorrow I'll start another one of your 30 day yoga journeys and everything will be right with the world.

Like may others I‚Äôm sure, when you said this was unguided I was disappointed and thought ‚Äúuh, I can‚Äôt really do that‚Äù - then throughout, I kept hearing Adriene‚Äôs voice in my head with the phrases reminding us how to do it. The biggest ones were ‚ÄúYou have everything you need‚Äù and ‚ÄúYou got this‚Äù. I‚Äôve completed the 30 days, thinking I was teaching my body, but didn‚Äôt realise Adriene was teaching me how to do ALL of it. That‚Äôs the mark of a really skilled teacher for me, where you don‚Äôt even realise they are teaching you. Just remarkable. I also noticed how beautifully deliberately all the poses were completed, allowing us to see key elements that would prompt our memory.

What stuns me is how all of that has been accomplished on a channel that is also not worried about being relaxed, having the giggles, saying the wrong phrase, or generally drifting off course for a moment. I couldn‚Äôt help noticing the smiles on her face throughout, and I really hope that was because she knew how many would be watching it and being amazed at how much they could now do.

Huge kudos on the whole production as well. The camera work that made sure you could see the moves, only changing when it was important to do so. The choice to make the final one as the sun was setting, somehow so lovely for the last one, and allowing the reflections in the glass to just add more to the beauty of it. And finally, that fact that the closing beats of the music have been used as the intro throughout, so as it ends we‚Äôre reminded of all the beginnings. 

You have told us all that we‚Äôre amazing. I‚Äôll take that, but you guys are utterly amazing as well. Talent and skill at a level that it appears subtle and simple. Thank you again. (And Benji muscling in for some love part way through just seemed so perfect üëå)

Day 30 is always the worst for me. First, thank you Adriene (and team) for making this happen. This is the third year I've done your 30 day "journey" although I've never done it as each day was released, as I did this year. I come back to these videos all year to try and keep focused and I am grateful that you make them with such care. I do have to say the last day of these things always make me feel like a failure. Even though I've been doing this with you for three years I don't feel like I'm good at doing it on my own. I get distracted, never know how long to hold postures, or what to do next. Listening to music and doing Yoga unguided is not something that works for me. So instead, I always end the journey with a sore neck (from constantly trying to keep an eye on the video) and deflated because it's always such a terrible practice for me. Maybe I am the only one like this and I just suck at Yoga, but I really wish there was another option. Is there no way to release the video (or a second video) with some sort of minimal guide Voice Over or something like that?  I get the point of it being minimal, but having to watch the video constantly for guidance defeats the point, and hurts.

I hope you don't take this the wrong way. I love this time on the mat, and I am just trying to share my experience now (3 years running). Maybe you'll consider us novice practitioners in this final video next time, as you do so well up to Day 29. Anyway, thanks again. Hope this helps. Have a great year. :)

Adrienne, you amazing human being! I was planning on doing this session tomorrow just because of a stressful schedule and not being in the right state for yoga BUT I am so glad I pushed myself to get on the mat because it was exactly what I needed. I am so grateful for your dedication and for having found your youtube channel when I was just getting started with recovering from my eating disorder a couple of years ago. Since then you have been with me on good days but mostly bad ones, keeping me calm and and sane in the storm.

I feel sentimental thinking back to some of those horrible days when getting on the mat was the last thing I wanted to do (I used to work out 3-4 hours a day so I decided to do yoga as a substitute at home when my doctor told me I needed to rest since it was still movement). Today I have come so far and when I get on the mat it's because I love it and because I genuinely want to learn to love my body and, for me, the road to acceptance is found through moving and being present in and with myself.

You have taught me all of those things and I can honestly say that that has been more beneficial than any visit to a psychiatrist. So know, and I'm sure you do but it can be repeated over and over, know that you aren't just teaching us the tools of yoga and moving in a way that feels good - you are teaching us to accept and love ourselves in our own company, teaching us to find a breath that calms and most importantly - teaching us that we are all worth it, worthy of being happy and content with ourselves. <3

Sorry for a long post but I really want you to know how important your work is. And I am so grateful that I have you (and Benji!) in my life. It means the world to me. See you on the mat many more days to come. It doesn't end here!

It's impossible not to get emotional the last day of the program, especially if you've been doing this 30 day experience for 4 years in a row and you've been going through a lot. I started with Kundalini yoga, but I can say for sure that you, Adriene, ignited my passion for Ashtanga (even if I Iike when you mix it up a bit!). I didn't want to share this, but I'm going to do it, hoping it could be of some help: I'm a fitness lover and I usually train 6 days week, but last summer I lost my father. I didn't have the physical and psychological strength to workout for weeks, the only thing I could do was yoga: in the darkest time of my life, it helped me investigating my heart, facing the grief and embracing the advice that my dad gave me: to live in the moment, because the present is the only time we really own. It's  not easy, but this is what I'll be working on this year. So thank you, Adriene: I send my love to you, to Benji and to all the people around the world who participated in this program. And remember everyone: maybe yoga is not THE ONLY WAY to heal your heart and your soul, but is for sure A WAY to get up on your feet when life smashes you down on the floor. Namaste.

I learned so much from you and from myself, that I kept a journal, writing down a thing that I learned or realized after each video, each day. I am now able to transfer that wisdom and that curiosity off the mat and into my daily life. My jaw tension is gone and my back pain only reappears once a week, and the next yoga practise wipes it away. I am in awe and I could not be more thankful for this experience and the whole community travelling along. I got into my own flow today, practising mostly with my eyes closed, and everytime I saw you on the screen it made me so very happy. All my love, Martha

Adrienne, you are amazing and the community you've built is absolutely incredible. I've tried committing to the 30 days for the past 4 years and never made it past the first two weeks. This year, however, on the heels of a 3 month solo journey abroad, something clicked. I stopped thinking about this as a "workout" but rather as a self-care and mental health practice. Quickly my day didn't feel complete without some "quiet time in my love cave" haha. Like many others in the comments, this final practice made me really emotional. I began with a gratitude meditation with tears streaming down my face and ended the same way. I am so proud of myself for sticking with this. I've found myself finally applying breathwork to my daily life off the mat and was shocked by how much my physical strength and balance have improved in just 30 days. Thank you, thank you, thank you. Unfortunately as a student I really couldn't afford to pay for classes on my budget. I was also so self-conscious about how often I'd fall out of poses due to an injury on the job to my left hip, so I was often too self conscious to do yoga with others. Still, I was determined to do this for myself. That's when I found this channel! 

I did it on and off over the years and it helped keep me fit while teaching overseas. This past November I decided I'd really commit to it and do 30 minutes a day. In January when Dedicate started, I bumped that up to a full hour a day. Not only is the weakness in my injured hip gone, but I just feel so light in body and mind. I feel so strong and energetic! Now my sister and I are saving up to take a trip together to Nepal to start our yoga instructor training. <3 I wouldn't be this version of me that I respect and honor without you. From the bottom of my heart, thank you so much for everything you do.

This was my first 30 day yoga journey, but certainly will not be my last. I'm so proud of myself for completing each practice, though I did do days 22-25 all on day 25.  During that time, my mom had fallen down the stairs and broke her wrist and badly sprained her ankle. I was having a really hard time dealing with everything that was involved with that situation and I'd be lying if I said I wasn't slightly traumatized from the experience. I felt a lot of guilt for skipping those days, but then so much relief when I caught up and got back to caring for myself too. There's a lot of pressure involving my aging mom who has both physical and mental disabilities, and even harder without any other family to help out. I'm so lucky to have a supportive husband who reminds me of what I should and shouldn't help her with as I've done too much for her the past year causing her to unnecessarily rely on me for certain things. I'm learning where I have to draw boundaries, not just for her but for my own sanity. I love your frequent message of needing to take care for ourselves first so that we can better help others. I have everything I need and more to continue with this amazingly therapeutic form of self-care, including a much nicer yoga mat that I ordered a couple weeks ago and left wrapped up to start using once this series ended, as well as an annual subscription to your site. Thank you so much, Adriene and the team. You've helped me in more ways than you know.

Dearest Adriene,
How can a human being who I have never met in person. who I can only see on a two dimensional screen, make me feel as though she is sitting right beside me, as though she is a dear friend who I trust wholly and completely?  When I read your love letter this morning, I felt both anxious and a sense of calm, with part of me not wanting to go through the morning without your voice to guide me, and the other part knowing it would be, and still another part knowing that your voice was guiding me to hear my own.  I settled in, and when you walked onto the mat and looked at the camera and smiled, it was as though you were in the room with me, and I too, smiled as I began to cry... and then flow.  


I have been practicing yoga in a very off and on kind of way for 20 years.  In those years, I have often said that I love how yoga makes me feel and wish that I would discipline myself and make it a regular habit.  I discovered your videos on YouTube about six months ago when I decided to stop paying for a gym membership I wasn't getting my money's worth from because it felt like another thing to check off the daily to-do list, rather than something I yearned to do.  Any day I carved out time for yoga, I would scroll through your list of videos and pick whatever my soul said yes to.  On New Year's Day, I happened to need some guidance, and that is when I discovered your invitation to this 30 day journey.  There was no debate, no struggle - my soul simply welcomed the invitation and signed on with an open heart.


I didn't miss a day.  This is the first time in all my years that I haven't felt a struggle to commit to something I wanted.  And I know that this journey will continue, because of you.  Yes, yes, of course - because of me, (smile) - but a student needs a guide, and a soul needs inspiration.  


The work you are doing is such a gift on this planet.  I am so inspired by you and thankful to have discovered you.  Thank you for contributing to the love and health and well being of this planet.  Thank you for your compassion and creativity and heart. Oh, wow! I'd never tried this before. (I love not looking at the screen and just following instructions.) This time I took the chance, and I learned so much! 1. My body knows exactly what it wants and I can listen in and just go with the flow. 2. I can grow poses out of other poses, and it feels very natural and good. 3. Moments of unexpected synchronicity happen! After a while I diverged from the video and just went with whatever my body was craving, and sometimes I looked up and Adriene was doing the same. We're both trees! Like a beautiful mirror. 4. Sometimes I look up, and we're doing different things. And even though I'm a lizard, or a pigeon, and you are a humble warrior, I know where you are and what that feels like. I had such zen moments. It was awesome. I also noticed how much more mindful some of my poses have become, even tabletop position. And how every recurring downward dog feels softer and longer. And last but not least: I can come down into self-care and self-love mode and just enjoy the developing softness and warmth and then relax and let go. Thank you so much, Adriene, and everyone who has been on this journey with me. I don't usually write such novels, but I'm seriously filled with love and gratitude right now. Namaste. x
